TY  - JOUR
T1  - Ties, Leaders, And Time In Teams: Strong Inference About Network Structure’s Effects On Team Viability And Performance
AU  - Balkundi, Prasad
AU  - Harrison, David A.
Y1  - 2006/02/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2006.20785500
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2006.20785500
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 49
EP  - 68
VL  - 49
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - How do members? and leaders? social network structures help or hinder team effectiveness? A meta-analysis of 37 studies of teams in natural contexts suggests that teams with densely configured interpersonal ties attain their goals better and are more committed to staying together; that is, team task performance and viability are both higher. Further, teams with leaders who are central in the teams? intergroup networks and teams that are central in their intergroup network tend to perform better. Time sequencing, member familiarity, and tie content moderate structure-performance connections. Results suggest stronger incorporation of social network concepts into theories about team effectiveness.
AB  - How do members? and leaders? social network structures help or hinder team effectiveness? A meta-analysis of 37 studies of teams in natural contexts suggests that teams with densely configured interpersonal ties attain their goals better and are more committed to staying together; that is, team task performance and viability are both higher. Further, teams with leaders who are central in the teams? intergroup networks and teams that are central in their intergroup network tend to perform better. Time sequencing, member familiarity, and tie content moderate structure-performance connections. Results suggest stronger incorporation of social network concepts into theories about team effectiveness.
